rier 1485":"23 februari 1485","1176":"1176","1471":"1471","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","1434":"1434","about 1459":"circa 1459","1510":"1510","1486":"1486","1574":"1574","1134":"1134","about 1510":"circa 1510","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","St Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1459–about 1510":"about 1459–about 1510","1134–1176":"1134–1176","1459–1510":"1459–1510","1471–1510":"1471–1510","1486–Female":"1486–Deceased","1508–1574":"1508–1574","1429–Male":"1429–Deceased","1434–1479":"1434–1479","23 février 1485":"23 February 1485","1176":"1176","1471":"1471","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","1434":"1434","about 1459":"about 1459","1510":"1510","1486":"1486","1574":"1574","1134":"1134","about 1510":"about 1510","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","St Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sainte-","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."],"variants":[{"name":"Santee","meanings":["Probably an altered form of French <b>Santé</b> (see   Sante  ) or of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname.","In some cases also an Americanized form of Italian   Santi  ."]},{"name":"Saint","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicolas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicolas de Sainte- Aldegonde was born about 1459, in Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Jacques de Sainte- Aldegonde, was 31 and his mother, Elisabeth Blondel, was 26. He married Honorine de Montmorency on 23 February 1485, in France. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died about 1510, in his hometown, at the age of 53."},"et":{"about 1459–about 1510":"umbes 1459–umbes 1510","1134–1176":"1134–1176","1459–1510":"1459–1510","1471–1510":"1471–1510","1486–Female":"1486–Surnud","1508–1574":"1508–1574","1429–Male":"1429–Surnud","1434–1479":"1434–1479","23 février 1485":"23. veebruar 1485","1176":"1176","1471":"1471","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","1434":"1434","about 1459":"umbes 1459","1510":"1510","1486":"1486","1574":"1574","1134":"1134","about 1510":"umbes 1510","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","St Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1459–about 1510":"noin 1459–noin 1510","1134–1176":"1134–1176","1459–1510":"1459–1510","1471–1510":"1471–1510","1486–Female":"1486–Kuollut","1508–1574":"1508–1574","1429–Male":"1429–Kuollut","1434–1479":"1434–1479","23 février 1485":"23. helmikuuta 1485","1176":"1176","1471":"1471","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","1434":"1434","about 1459":"noin 1459","1510":"1510","1486":"1486"